body:
Thanks for your fast response!

Assuming with have a model Product and a  yii\web\Controller based controller with following action:
 ```php
    public function actionProducts()
    {
        $products = Product::find();

        $limit = Yii::$app->request->get('limit', 100);
        $start = Yii::$app->request->get('start', 0);
        $sort  = Yii::$app->request->get('sort', null);

        if ($limit > 0) {
            $products->limit(intval($limit));
        }
        if ($start > 0) {
            $products->offset(intval($start));
        }
        if ($sort != null) {
            $sort = Json::decode($sort);
            foreach ($sort as $s) {
                $products->addOrderBy($s['property'].' '.$s['direction']);
            }
        }
        /* ... some filtering code ... */

        $response = [
            'products' => $products->asArray()->all(),
            'total' => $products->count()
        ];
        Yii::$app->response->format = 'json';
        return $response;
    }
````

In our db are 1000 products for example.

Calling the action with `https://.../products?limit=10&sort[{"property":"name","direction":"DESC"}]`
returns prior Yii: 2.0.11:
`{"products":[{ .... 10 products ....}],"total":"1000"}`
and now:
`{"products":[{ .... 10 products ....}],"total":"10"}`

We are aware that we could unset limit, offset, orderBy like it is done by Yii in ActiveDataProvider::prerpareTotalCount() for example, but actually the update to the current Yii version breaks our code.

I can't check with tests until I'm home but I wonder if removing the `empty($this->groupBy)` conditional and clearing the `orderBy` before the `createCommand` would work.

```php
protected function queryScalar($selectExpression, $db)
    {
        if ($this->emulateExecution) {
            return null;
        }
        if (
            !$this->distinct
            && empty($this->groupBy)
            && empty($this->having)
            && empty($this->union)
        ) {
            $select = $this->select;
            $limit = $this->limit;
            $offset = $this->offset;
//
            $order = $this->orderBy;
//
            $this->select = [$selectExpression];
            $this->limit = null;
            $this->offset = null;
//
            $this->orderBy = null;
//
            $command = $this->createCommand($db);
            $this->select = $select;
            $this->limit = $limit;
            $this->offset = $offset;
//
            $this->orderBy = $order;
//
            return $command->queryScalar();
        } else {
            return (new Query)->select([$selectExpression])
                ->from(['c' => $this])
                ->createCommand($db)
                ->queryScalar();
        }
    }
```

I don't agree this is a bug though (it is definitely an undocumented BC breaking change).

Count should return the exact same number as the number of results.
So this should hold:
````
foreach($everyInstanceOfQuery as $q) {
    count($q->all()) === $q->count();
}
````

Side note, I don't see the reason for 2 implementations in `yii\db\Query`. I expect the database to always optimize, wrapping stuff in an extra query shouldn't make a difference:
````
// "Unoptimized"
SELECT count(*) FROM (select * from t)
// "Optimized"
SELECT count(*) FROM from t;
````

MySQL explain: `Select tables optimized away`

@samdark as you closed the issue, what would be the most reasonable way following the best practices handling this case?

Doing what @SamMousa suggested?

That would work on the majority of the cases, however, when processing a large batch results that may seem noticeable.
